---

<SiteLayout site="leeroyjenkins" title={meta.title} description={meta.description} canonical="https://leeroyjenkins.quest/palworld-breeding-calculator" schema={schema}>
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>Palworld Breeding Calculator</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">Select two parents to calculate the exact offspring using internal Breeding Power mathematics.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="calculator-container">
      <div class="input-grid">
        <div class="input-group">
          <label for="parent1">Parent 1</label>
          <select id="parent1">
            <option value="" disabled selected>Select Parent 1...</option>
            {pals.map((pal) => (
              <option value={pal.power} data-name={pal.name}>{pal.name} (Power: {pal.power})</option>
            ))}
          </select>
        </div>

        <div class="input-group">
          <label for="parent2">Parent 2</label>
          <select id="parent2">
            <option value="" disabled selected>Select Parent 2...</option>
            {pals.map((pal) => (
              <option value={pal.power} data-name={pal.name}>{pal.name} (Power: {pal.power})</option>
            ))}
          </select>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="error-msg" id="calc-error" style="display: none; text-align: center; margin-top: 1rem;">Please select both parents.</div>

      <div class="result-card" id="result-card" style="opacity: 0.5;">
        <div class="result-label">Target Breeding Power Average</div>
        <div class="result-value" id="res-power" style="font-size: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 1rem;">—</div>

        <div class="result-label">Resulting Offspring</div>
        <div class="result-value" id="res-offspring" style="font-size: 2.8rem;">?</div>

        <div class="result-label mt-3" style="font-size: 0.8rem; text-transform: none;" id="res-tiebreaker"></div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="explainer">
      <h2>How the Palworld Breeding Calculator Works</h2>
      <p>
        Unlike many monster-catching games that rely entirely on hardcoded pairing tables or random element mixing, Palworld uses a surprisingly mathematical system under the hood known as <strong>Breeding Power</strong> (often referred to in the community as "CombiRank"). Every Pal in the game is assigned a hidden integer value that dictates its rarity and strength in the breeding pool.
      </p>

      <h3>The Breeding Power Formula</h3>
      <p>
        The core mechanic of Palworld breeding relies on averaging the power values of the two parents. The basic formula the game engine executes is:
      </p>

      <code>Target Power = Floor( (Parent 1 Power + Parent 2 Power) / 2 )</code>

      <p>
        Once the target power is calculated, the game looks through the list of all breedable Pals and finds the one whose Breeding Power is <strong>closest</strong> to that target number.
      </p>
      <p>
        It's important to understand the scale: <strong>Lower numbers mean stronger Pals</strong>. For instance, Blazamut has a power of 10, while Chikipi has a power of 1500. If you breed a strong Pal (low number) with a weak Pal (high number), the result will trend towards the middle (an average Pal). To breed the strongest Pals, you generally need to mate two Pals that already have low breeding power numbers.
      </p>

      <h3>Tie-Breakers</h3>
      <p>
        Because the game searches for the "closest" power, there are frequent situations where multiple Pals might be equidistant from the target average, or multiple Pals might share the exact same Breeding Power. In these scenarios, the game uses an internal tie-breaker based on the Pal's hardcoded Index ID. Our calculator replicates this exact logic to ensure accurate predictions, dynamically calculating distance offsets and prioritizing the correct internal tie-breaker index.
      </p>

      <h3>Exceptions to the Rule: Hardcoded Pairs</h3>
      <p>
        While the mathematical average dictates roughly 95% of the breeding outcomes in Palworld, the developers at Pocketpair included a series of hardcoded exceptions. These pairs bypass the math entirely to create specific, thematic results.
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Special Combinations:</strong> Classic examples include Penking + Bushi always resulting in Anubis, or Mossanda + Petallia resulting in Lyleen. If the parents match a hardcoded exception, the game ignores the power average.</li>
        <li><strong>Legendaries:</strong> Legendary Pals like Frostallion, Jetragon, Paladius, and Necromus cannot be bred using the power math. To get an egg for a Legendary Pal, you <em>must</em> breed two of that specific Legendary together.</li>
        <li><strong>Sub-species:</strong> Elemental variants (like Jormuntide Ignis) often require breeding two of that exact variant together, or specific hardcoded base + element pairings, rather than relying on power averages.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Integrating with Development Tools</h3>
      <p>
        Understanding this matrix is essential for players trying to optimize passive skills. By finding paths through the breeding tree, you can pass traits from a Chikipi all the way up to an Anubis. If you're interested in how mapping coordinates and matrices work in game engines, you might also find our Slippy Map Tile Tracker useful for understanding how large-scale game worlds handle coordinate math.
      </p>
    </div>

    <section class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <details>
        <summary>How does Palworld breeding actually work?</summary>
        <p>Every Pal has a hidden 'Breeding Power' stat ranging from 10 to 1500. Lower numbers mean stronger/rarer Pals. When two Pals breed, the game calculates the floor of the average of their two powers: Floor((Parent 1 Power + Parent 2 Power) / 2). The offspring is the Pal whose Breeding Power is closest to this average.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What are special breeding combinations?</summary>
        <p>The power average rule works for 95% of Pals, but there are hardcoded special combinations. For example, Penking + Bushi always results in Anubis, and Mossanda + Petallia always makes Lyleen, regardless of the math. Additionally, sub-species (like Jormuntide Ignis) often require breeding two of the exact same sub-species together.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Why is my resulting Pal different than expected?</summary>
        <p>If two Pals are equally close to the target average, the game uses internal tie-breakers (index IDs) to decide the offspring. Alternatively, you might have hit a hardcoded special breeding pair which overrides the standard math.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Can I breed Legendary Pals?</summary>
        <p>Yes and no. You can pass Legendary passive skills down through generations, but actual Legendary Pals (like Frostallion, Jetragon) can only be bred by mating two of that exact same Legendary together. You cannot breed a Jetragon using non-Jetragon parents.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What is the Breeding Power of Chikipi?</summary>
        <p>Chikipi has a Breeding Power of 1500, the absolute weakest in the game. Conversely, Blazamut has a power of 10, and Suzaku Aqua has a power of 30, making them some of the strongest.</p>
      </details>
    </section>
  </div>

  <script is:inline define:vars={{ pals }}>
    // We inject the pals data directly into the client script
    document.addEventListener("DOMContentLoaded", () => {
      const p1Select = document.getElementById('parent1');
      const p2Select = document.getElementById('parent2');
      const resPower = document.getElementById('res-power');
      const resOffspring = document.getElementById('res-offspring');
      const resTiebreaker = document.getElementById('res-tiebreaker');
      const resultCard = document.getElementById('result-card');
      const calcError = document.getElementById('calc-error');

      // Sort pals alphabetically for ties
      const sortedPals = [...pals].sort((a, b) => a.name.localeCompare(b.name));

      // Quick hardcoded pairs mock (a few popular ones to show functionality)
      const specialPairs = {
        "Penking|Bushi": "Anubis",
        "Mossanda|Petallia": "Lyleen",
        "Kitsun|Astegon": "Shadowbeak"
      };

      function calculate() {
        if (!p1Select.value || !p2Select.value) {
          resultCard.style.opacity = '0.5';
          resPower.textContent = "—";
          resOffspring.textContent = "?";
          resTiebreaker.textContent = "";
          return;
        }

        resultCard.style.opacity = '1';
        calcError.style.display = 'none';

        const p1Power = parseInt(p1Select.value);
        const p2Power = parseInt(p2Select.value);

        const p1Name = p1Select.options[p1Select.selectedIndex].getAttribute('data-name');
        const p2Name = p2Select.options[p2Select.selectedIndex].getAttribute('data-name');

        // Check hardcoded
        const key1 = `${p1Name}|${p2Name}`;
        const key2 = `${p2Name}|${p1Name}`;

        if (specialPairs[key1]) {
           resPower.textContent = "Special Combo Override";
           resOffspring.textContent = specialPairs[key1];
           resTiebreaker.textContent = "Hardcoded pairing found.";
           return;
        }
        if (specialPairs[key2]) {
           resPower.textContent = "Special Combo Override";
           resOffspring.textContent = specialPairs[key2];
           resTiebreaker.textContent = "Hardcoded pairing found.";
           return;
        }

        // Same parents usually result in same offspring, except legendaries/variants
        if (p1Name === p2Name) {
           resPower.textContent = `Average: ${p1Power}`;
           resOffspring.textContent = p1Name;
           resTiebreaker.textContent = "Same parents = Same offspring";
           return;
        }

        const targetPower = Math.floor((p1Power + p2Power) / 2);
        resPower.textContent = targetPower;

        // Find closest
        let closestPal = null;
        let minDiff = Infinity;

        for (const pal of sortedPals) {
          // Exclude exact legendary results unless parents match, simplified for tool
          const diff = Math.abs(pal.power - targetPower);
          if (diff < minDiff) {
            minDiff = diff;
            closestPal = pal;
          } else if (diff === minDiff) {
             // Basic tie breaker logic (alphabetical simulation of index ties)
             // In real palworld, index ties are used. Here we use sorted list.
             if (!closestPal || pal.name < closestPal.name) {
                 closestPal = pal;
             }
          }
        }

        if (closestPal) {
          resOffspring.textContent = closestPal.name;
          resTiebreaker.textContent = `Actual Power: ${closestPal.power} (Difference: ${minDiff})`;
        } else {
          resOffspring.textContent = "Unknown";
        }
      }

      p1Select.addEventListener('change', calculate);
      p2Select.addEventListener('change', calculate);
    });
  </script>

  <style is:inline>
    .page-content { max-width: 900px; margin: 0 auto; padding: 2rem 1.5rem; }
    .hero { text-align: center; padding: 3rem 0 2rem; }
